caption: Walked right in around 1:30 pm on a sunday, no reservation no problems, seated fast, No menu have to scan it from a small cardboard at the table but no one told us so it was awkward, sun is really bright against the windows but staff was attentive and brought down the electric shade which  made it much more comfortable. ordered pulpo tostatdas, wife ordered chicken sandwich and fries, food came out quick, pulpo tostatdas were good, but not enough to satisfy for 18 bucks, chicken sandwich was huge and well done, steak fries taste good and had a good amount... maybe more sauces and a coleslaw to compliment the sandwich but over all not bad will go again to try dinner...

It gets two stars for the decor and awesome DJ/Music! But other than that, it’s expensive dog food. I can see how someone that’s not used to fine dining be impressed. They need to improve their menu, and bring out fully cooked food, and make sure the food lives up to its price, because $200 for some empanadas that were gross, and rice with no flavor, and plain plantain that was nothing out of this world. Ehh.

Reception: could have been a lot better. I made reservations for 9pm, upon arrival there were a couple of other people waiting to be seated, none of which had reservations. What is the point of having a reservation system if you’re going to prioritize based on arrival?  Service: The restaurant was relatively busy so perhaps that will account for how long the food took to arrive. However, when our entrees came in one of my companions received the wrong side order, and somehow they sent an extra entree no one ordered.  Food: I will say that since this is a fusion restaurant, you shouldn’t expect the flavors to match what you would expect to see in a traditional Latin place. That aside it wasn’t bad. I ordered a beef and sweet plantain mofongo, which was absolutely delicious.  One of my companions did say that the rice tasted pre-packaged.  Overall: The food is not bad and the overall atmosphere is also quite nice. However, at the price point I do expect service to be much better than it was.

Disappointed.  A friend planned her birthday dinner at Suyo based on the great reviews.  She requested the VIP area after assuming it would be the best area in the restaurant, it was not.  The VIP was in a hot corner upstairs.  The tables for 14 people were set in an "L" shape, which lead to some giving their backs to others in our party.  The space was extremely warm, not a single piece of decor on the walls.  Unfortunately, we went for a prefix menu below, $55 each for a 2 course meal, 1 hour sangria.  The appetizers were wings and Asian guacamole w/wonton chip,  we should've known better.  Guacamole belongs to Mexico not any Asian, it was inedible.  Extremely salty, brownish in color, with sesame seeds and who knows what other sacrilege.  The wings were good, but definitely not enough for 14 guests.  The main course options were limited.  Most of the table ordered the churrasco, afterall Chile Rellendo ($16 on their regular menu) would not have been a smart choice.  The churrasco was way too chewy and nothing special.  One hour drinks for $20 was ok, but you probably won't be able to order more than 2 glasses in an hour unless you chug.  The busboys were extremely slow to pick up plates, we had to ask several times for our appetizer plates to be picked up.  Last shocker, the waitress offered to cut a small cake the birthday had to share with her guest, of course we took the offer.  They charged us $20 without informing there was a cake cutting fee, that's a first!  Very sneaky, had we known we would have cut our own cake!  Truly disappointed.  They place may be nice inside but their food and service left little to desire.
